SECOND REGULAR SESSION
SENATE BILL NO. 1668
103RD GENERA L ASSEMBLY
INTRODUCED BY SENATOR GREGORY (21).
7173S.01I KRISTINA MARTIN, Secretary
AN ACT
To amend chapter 620, RSMo, by adding thereto nine new sections relating to downtown
redevelopment incentives.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Missouri, as follows:
1 Section A. Chapter 620, RSMo, is amended by adding thereto
2 nine new sections, to be known as sections 620.6000, 620.6003,
3 620.6006, 620.6009, 620.6012, 620.6015, 620.6018, 620.6021, and
4 620.6024, to read as follows:
1 620.6000. 1. Sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be
2 known and may be cited as the "Missouri Innovation, Public
3 Safety, and Accountability Act".
4 2. As used in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024, the
5 following terms mean:
6 (1) "Application", a written submission by a project
7 sponsor seeking one or more economic development incentives
8 authorized under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 for a project
9 located within an innovation district, consisting of:
10 (a) A description of the proposed project;
11 (b) Documentation sufficient to demonstrate
12 eligibility for the incentives sought; and
13 (c) Information necessary to evaluate the project
14 under the master scorecard. An application shall be deemed
15 submitted upon delivery in the form prescribed by rule and

SB 1668 2
16 shall not be deemed incomplete except for failure to provide
17 information expressly required by such rule;
18 (2) "City", any incorporated city, town, or
19 municipality organized under the laws of the state of
20 Missouri;
21 (3) "Department", the Missouri department of economic
22 development;
23 (4) "Executive branch", the chief executive officer of
24 a participating city and any department, agency, or officer
25 acting under the authority of such chief executive officer,
26 consistent with the city's form of government to administer,
27 oversee, and carry out the responsibilities of an innovation
28 district authorized under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024;
29 (5) "Innovation district", a locally designated
30 geographic area within a participating city that overlays
31 its historic downtown, central business district, or
32 Missouri main street district, as applicable;
33 (6) "Innovation district master plan", a locally
34 prepared plan submitted by the executive branch to the
35 department under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024, identifying
36 district boundaries, existing conditions, and reinvestment
37 priorities within the innovation district;
38 (7) "Main street district", an accredited, associated,
39 or affiliated main street district of the Missouri main
40 street program created under sections 251.470 to 251.485;
41 (8) "Master scorecard", the framework established
42 under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 for evaluating project-
43 level development incentives within an innovation district;
44 (9) "Participating city", a city that has voluntarily
45 elected to establish an innovation district and is eligible
46 to participate in programs authorized under sections
47 620.6000 to 620.6024;

SB 1668 3
48 (10) "Reviewing authority", the local governing body,
49 commission, board, or state agency authorized by law to
50 approve or administer an incentive for which an application
51 is submitted.
52 3. There is hereby established the "Innovation
53 District Program", a framework through which cities may
54 qualify for state-authorized economic incentives.
55 4. No city shall be required to establish an
56 innovation district. A city that elects to participate
57 shall do so in partnership with the state and in accordance
58 with the requirements of sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 and
59 applicable rules promulgated by the department.
60 5. Nothing in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be
61 construed to supersede local authority over land use,
62 zoning, or building codes.
63 6. (1) A city may apply to the department for
64 designation of an innovation district by submitting an
65 innovation district master plan for approval under the
66 requirements of this section.
67 (2) No local legislative act, ordinance, or resolution
68 shall be required as a prerequisite to designation of an
69 innovation district under this section.
70 (3) Upon approval of the innovation district master
71 plan by the department, the innovation district shall be
72 deemed designated for purposes of sections 620.6000 to
73 620.6024.
74 (4) The executive branch shall:
75 (a) Prepare and submit the innovation district master
76 plan;
77 (b) Coordinate with the department and local reviewing
78 authorities regarding district-level implementation;

SB 1668 4
79 (c) Provide oversight of district-level reinvestment
80 mechanisms authorized under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024;
81 and
82 (d) Perform such other functions as may be necessary
83 to carry out the purposes of the innovation district program.
84 7. An innovation district master plan submitted to the
85 department shall include:
86 (1) The proposed innovation district geographic
87 boundaries;
88 (2) Identification of vacant or underutilized property
89 for the purpose of demonstrating where and how incentives
90 authorized under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 are expected
91 to be deployed and the impact such incentives are intended
92 to have;
93 (3) Public safety and infrastructure priorities;
94 (4) A general strategy for surplus or incremental
95 state revenues captured under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024;
96 and
97 (5) High-level projections of anticipated housing
98 units, jobs, business, and population impacts.
99 8. A city shall not be permitted more than one
100 innovation district and the department shall not consider
101 multiple proposals from a city.
102 9. The department's approval authority shall be
103 limited to determining whether the proposed innovation
104 district boundaries are reasonable in geography and are
105 generally consistent with this section. All other
106 information required to be included in the master plan shall
107 be informational in nature and shall not be subject to
108 discretionary approval, modification, or denial by the
109 department. The department shall approve the innovation
110 district master plan within forty-five calendar days of

SB 1668 5
111 receipt of a complete application. Failure to act within
112 this period shall constitute automatic approval, provided
113 the submitted plan satisfies all applicable requirements.
114 10. (1) Upon designation of an innovation district,
115 the following state-administered incentives shall be made
116 available within the district, subject to the terms of
117 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 and administered by the
118 applicable state agency:
119 (a) Missouri income tax exemption;
120 (b) Missouri opportunity zone;
121 (c) Office-to-residential tax credit;
122 (d) State sales tax reinvestment and withholdings
123 reinvestment, where authorized; and
124 (e) Any other incentive expressly authorized by state
125 law to be administered by a state agency within an
126 innovation district.
127 (2) Upon designation of an innovation district, the
128 following locally administered incentives may be made
129 available within the district, subject to the terms of
130 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 and administered by the
131 applicable local governing body:
132 (a) Property tax abatement; and
133 (b) Tax increment financing.
134 (3) Eligibility for incentives within an innovation
135 district shall be determined on a project-by-project basis.
136 (4) Upon designation of an innovation district, the
137 incentives under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall apply
138 within the district to otherwise eligible projects by
139 operation of law. No ordinance, resolution, policy, or
140 practice adopted by a participating city shall have the
141 effect of limiting, suspending, conditioning, or rendering
142 unavailable any such incentives within the district.

SB 1668 6
143 11. (1) The department shall adopt and administer a
144 single, standardized master scorecard to evaluate incentives
145 for projects located within an innovation district. A
146 participating city and the department shall apply the master
147 scorecard uniformly and exclusively and shall not adopt,
148 substitute, supplement, or modify alternative scoring
149 criteria for such projects.
150 (2) The master scorecard shall apply only to the
151 following incentives authorized under state law and
152 administered or approved at the local or state level:
153 (a) Property tax abatement;
154 (b) Tax increment financing; and
155 (c) The office-to-residential tax credit.
156 (3) The master scorecard shall:
157 (a) Establish uniform criteria for evaluating project-
158 level incentives within the innovation district;
159 (b) Provide predictability and transparency regarding
160 baseline incentive eligibility;
161 (c) Rank projects based on measurable outcome;
162 (d) Establish intermediate incentive tiers for
163 projects scoring below the department's threshold for full
164 eligibility; and
165 (e) Assign project applications to incentive tiers
166 based on their normalized score, as established by rule of
167 the department.
168 (4) A project that achieves a normalized score of one
169 hundred points shall be entitled to the most favorable
170 incentive package available under state law for each
171 incentive governed by the master scorecard, subject only to
172 statutory limitations applicable to such incentive.
173 (5) Nothing in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be
174 construed to prohibit or limit a local governing authority

SB 1668 7
175 from awarding additional or enhanced local or locally
176 administered incentives beyond those indicated by a
177 project's score.
178 (6) Nothing in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be
179 construed to authorize the reduction, abatement, diversion,
180 or impairment of any existing revenues of the participating
181 city. Any property tax abatement or tax increment financing
182 incentive evaluated under the master scorecard shall apply
183 solely to net new assessed value, net new tax increment, or
184 net new property tax revenues.
185 (7) Any denial, limitation, reduction, or conditioning
186 of an incentive governed by this section that is based on
187 criteria inconsistent with the master scorecard or sections
188 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be invalid, and the applicant
189 shall be entitled to administrative and judicial remedies as
190 provided by law.
191 12. (1) The master scorecard shall evaluate projects
192 based on the following categories for purposes of
193 determining incentive tiers:
194 (a) Housing activation, rehabilitation, and creation;
195 (b) Affordability;
196 (c) Ground-floor activation and tenant improvements;
197 (d) Community improvements and neighborhood
198 connectivity;
199 (e) Historic preservation;
200 (f) Access, mobility, and infrastructure;
201 (g) Family-oriented design;
202 (h) Resident amenities and quality of life features;
203 (i) Economic impact and stabilization;
204 (j) Workforce practices, procurement, and stewardship.

SB 1668 8
205 The department shall assign point values to each category by
206 rule, consistent with this section. Applicability of
207 categories shall be determined under criteria established by
208 rule and shall not be subject to applicant election.
209 (2) No scoring category shall be weighed or applied in
210 a manner that:
211 (a) Accounts for a disproportionate share of the total
212 score;
213 (b) Causes the category to function as a mandatory
214 prerequisite for approval; or
215 (c) Has the practical effect of requiring a specific
216 policy outcome as a condition of receiving an incentive
217 governed by this section.
218 Participation in, or compliance with, any scoring category
219 including, but not limited to, affordability, prevailing
220 wage practices, or minority or women-owned business
221 participation shall be voluntary and encouraged only through
222 scoring and not as a requirement.
223 13. (1) The reviewing authority shall issue a written
224 determination approving or denying an application for
225 incentives under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 within forty-
226 five calendar days.
227 (2) Failure of a reviewing authority to issue a
228 written determination within the applicable review period
229 shall result in deemed approval of the application.
230 (3) If a reviewing authority fails to issue the
231 required ministerial confirmation of a deemed approval, the
232 department shall, upon request of the applicant, issue a
233 written certification of deemed approval within forty-five
234 calendar days. Failure of the department to issue such

SB 1668 9
235 certification within the prescribed period shall not impair
236 the effectiveness of the deemed approval.
1 620.6003. 1. In order to maintain designation as an
2 innovation district, a participating city shall, within six
3 months of designation, adopt, establish, or designate the
4 policies, processes, and authorities set forth in this
5 section and shall thereafter maintain such commitment on an
6 ongoing basis.
7 2. A participating city shall establish a fast-track
8 permitting process or "One-Stop Shop" for projects located
9 within an innovation district, which shall include
10 designation of a single, empowered point of contact, either
11 an individual or a designated group, within local
12 government, authorized to coordinate reviews and issue
13 binding determinations on behalf of all relevant
14 departments, agencies, and offices exercising permitting,
15 entitlement, inspection, or approval authority over the
16 project including, but not limited to, zoning, planning,
17 permitting, and building, fire, and life safety.
18 3. (1) The participating city shall provide:
19 (a) A clear and accessible application process;
20 (b) Coordinated interdepartmental review; and
21 (c) Issuance of an approval or denial within forty-
22 five calendar days of submission of a complete application.
23 (2) If a complete application is not approved or
24 denied within forty-five calendar days of submission, the
25 application shall be deemed approved by operation of law,
26 provided that the proposed project does not violate
27 applicable zoning requirements or life safety and fire
28 safety codes.

SB 1668 10
29 (3) Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to
30 waive or diminish compliance with zoning, structural, fire
31 safety, or life safety requirements.
32 4. (1) A participating city shall adopt a policy to
33 waive, reduce, or defer discretionary, duplicative, or
34 extraordinary permit and development fees for projects
35 located within the innovation district.
36 (2) Such policy shall not require waiver of fees
37 necessary to support the baseline health, staffing, and
38 operation of the building department or other reviewing
39 agencies, and may distinguish between essential operational
40 fees and discretionary or incremental charges.
41 5. (1) Any property subject to an existing tax
42 increment financing plan or tax abatement agreement at the
43 time of innovation district designation shall continue to be
44 governed by the terms of such existing agreement, and
45 nothing in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall be construed
46 to impair, modify, or terminate such agreement.
47 (2) For properties within an innovation district that
48 are not subject to an existing project-specific tax
49 increment financing plan or property tax abatement
50 agreement, fifty percent of the incremental increase in real
51 property tax revenues generated after designation shall be
52 treated as tax increment for purposes of deposit into the
53 applicable innovation district public safety fund,
54 established under section 620.6009. The reallocation of
55 such funds shall be determined by the executive branch under
56 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024.
57 (3) For new development or redevelopment projects
58 within an innovation district that are not subject to an
59 existing agreement, a project may elect, at the time of
60 project approval, whether to:

SB 1668 11
61 (a) Commence a project-specific tax increment
62 financing plan for the maximum term authorized by law;
63 (b) Commence a property-specific property tax
64 abatement for the maximum term authorized by law; or
65 (c) Proceed without either incentive.
66 Such election shall be voluntary and shall be made in
67 accordance with the incentive tier determined under the
68 master scorecard.
69 6. (1) A participating city shall adopt policies
70 providing building code flexibility for adaptive reuse
71 projects within an innovation district. Such policies shall:
72 (a) Permit performance-based compliance pathways,
73 particularly with respect to energy code requirements;
74 (b) Recognize the environmental and economic benefits
75 of embodied carbon savings associated with adaptive reuse;
76 and
77 (c) Maintain compliance with structural integrity,
78 fire safety, and life safety standards.
79 (2) Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to
80 require adoption of any specific building or energy code
81 standard.
82 7. (1) If the department determines that a
83 participating city has failed to adopt or maintain one or
84 more requirements of this section, the department shall
85 provide written notice of such noncompliance.
86 (2) The participating city shall have ninety calendar
87 days from receipt of such notice to cure the noncompliance.
88 (3) If the noncompliance is not cured within ninety
89 calendar days, the department may suspend the participating
90 city's innovation district designation until such time as
91 compliance is restored.

SB 1668 12
92 (4) Any suspension or revocation of innovation
93 district designation under this section shall apply
94 prospectively only and shall not:
95 (a) Impair, modify, or terminate any incentive,
96 agreement, approval, or benefit previously awarded;
97 (b) Affect the validity or enforceability of any
98 incentive, agreement, approval, or benefit previously
99 awarded; or
100 (c) Give rise to any claim for damages against an
101 applicant arising solely from the suspension or revocation
102 of district designation.
103 (5) Projects that have received approval or entered
104 into binding agreements in reliance on innovation district
105 designation prior to notice of noncompliance shall be
106 permitted to proceed in accordance with the terms of such
107 approvals or agreements.
108 8. (1) The department shall prepare and submit a
109 biennial written report to the general assembly summarizing
110 the status, performance, and outcomes of the innovation
111 district program. The purpose of the report is to provide
112 transparency, accountability, and aggregate evaluation
113 regarding the implementation and performance of innovation
114 districts and the incentives authorized under sections
115 620.6000 to 620.6024. The report shall be informational in
116 nature and shall not be used to impose additional approval
117 requirements, conditions, or penalties on any innovation
118 district or approved projects.
119 (2) Information included in the report shall be
120 presented in aggregate or summary form, by district and
121 statewide where appropriate, and shall not disclose
122 confidential taxpayer information or identify individual
123 projects unless otherwise required by law.

SB 1668 13
124 (3) The report shall include, to the extent reasonably
125 available, the following categories of information:
126 (a) The number of innovation districts designated and
127 the communities participating during the reporting period;
128 (b) The number and types of projects approved within
129 innovation districts and the distribution of incentive tiers
130 authorized under the master scorecard;
131 (c) Aggregate counts of housing, commercial, or mixed-
132 use activation, and other redevelopment occurring within
133 innovation districts;
134 (d) Aggregate counts of employment impacts, including
135 net new or retained employment where such data is available;
136 (e) A summary of public safety, infrastructure, or
137 other public investment activities undertaken within
138 innovation districts under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024; and
139 (f) Any observations or recommendations the department
140 determines may assist the general assembly in evaluating the
141 effectiveness of the program.
142 9. The department may retain, subject to
143 appropriation, a limited portion of net new state revenues
144 generated under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 solely for the
145 administration of the innovation district program. Such
146 retained amounts shall be derived exclusively from net new
147 economic activity attributable to innovation districts and
148 shall not reduce or impair any existing state or local
149 revenues. No application, participation, or administrative
150 fees shall be imposed under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024.
151 10. The department shall promulgate such rules and
152 regulations as are necessary to implement and administer
153 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024, provided that such rules are
154 consistent with and reasonably necessary to carry out the
155 purposes, structure, and operative provisions of sections

SB 1668 14
156 620.6000 to 620.6024. Any rule or portion of a rule, as
157 that term is defined in section 536.010, that is created
158 under the authority delegated in sections 620.6000 to
159 620.6024 shall become effective only if it complies with and
160 is subject to all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if
161 applicable, section 536.028. This section and chapter 536
162 are nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the
163 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay
164 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
165 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
166 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
167 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
168 11. Under section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
169 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under
170 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall sunset ten years after
171 the effective date of sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 unless
172 reauthorized by an act of the general assembly; and
173 (2) Sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 shall terminate on
174 September first of the calendar year immediately following
175 the calendar year in which the program authorized under
176 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 is sunset.
1 620.6006. 1. There is hereby established the "Rural
2 Missouri Development Fund", to be administered by the
3 department of economic development, for the purpose of
4 supporting economic development, infrastructure, housing,
5 workforce development, and related community-building
6 activities in rural and smaller communities throughout the
7 state.
8 2. (1) For purposes of this section, a "contributing
9 community" means a municipality that:
10 (a) Has designated one or more innovation districts
11 under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024; and

SB 1668 15
12 (b) Has a total certified assessed valuation that
13 ranks within the highest five percent of all Missouri
14 municipalities statewide, as most recently determined by the
15 Missouri state tax commission or the department of revenue.
16 (2) No municipality that does not meet both criteria
17 in subdivision (1) of this subsection shall be required to
18 contribute to the rural Missouri development fund.
19 3. (1) Each contributing community shall annually
20 contribute to the rural Missouri development fund an amount
21 equal to ten percent of net new property tax revenues
22 actually received by such communities that are generated
23 within its innovation district above the applicable baseline.
24 (2) For purposes of this section, "net new property
25 tax revenues actually received" means property tax revenues
26 collected and retained by the community that are
27 attributable to increases in assessed valuation occurring
28 upon designation of the innovation district.
29 (3) "Net new property tax revenues actually received"
30 shall not include:
31 (a) Any property tax revenues abated, exempted, or
32 otherwise forgone under a property tax abatement agreement;
33 or
34 (b) Any property tax increment captured, pledged, or
35 otherwise dedicated under a tax increment financing plan.
36 (4) Contributions under this section shall be derived
37 solely from collected incremental revenues and shall not
38 reduce or impair any existing property tax revenues, nor any
39 revenue subject to abatement or tax increment financing.
40 4. (1) Moneys in the rural Missouri development fund
41 may be awarded to:
42 (a) Rural municipalities;

SB 1668 16
43 (b) Smaller municipalities not meeting the definition
44 of a contributing community; or
45 (c) Local or regional development organizations,
46 community development corporations, or similar entities
47 applying on behalf of or in coordination with such
48 communities.
49 (2) Receipt of funds under this section shall not
50 require a community to establish an innovation district.
51 5. Funds awarded under this section may be used for
52 the following purposes including, but not limited to:
53 (1) Rural education;
54 (2) Public infrastructure improvements or public
55 safety;
56 (3) Housing development, rehabilitation, or
57 stabilization;
58 (4) Workforce development or training;
59 (5) Health care or community service facilities; and
60 (6) Other economic purposes consistent with the intent
61 of sections 620.6000 to 620.6024.
62 6. (1) The department of economic development shall
63 administer the rural Missouri development fund and shall
64 establish an application process for eligible recipients.
65 (2) In administering the fund, the department shall
66 consider:
67 (a) Project readiness;
68 (b) Demonstrated community need; and
69 (c) Alignment with the purposes of this section.
70 7. One percent of the revenue collected from the net
71 new property tax generated by a contributing community shall
72 be deposited into the fund for the department to be used
73 toward administrative fees to administer this section.

SB 1668 17
74 8. The department shall promulgate such rules and
75 regulations as are necessary to implement and administer
76 this section. Any rule or portion of a rule, as that term
77 is defined in section 536.010, that is created under the
78 authority delegated in this section shall become effective
79 only if it complies with and is subject to all of the
80 provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable, section
81 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are nonseverable and
82 if any of the powers vested with the general assembly
83 pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay the effective
84 date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are subsequently
85 held unconstitutional, then the grant of rulemaking
86 authority and any rule proposed or adopted after August 28,
87 2026, shall be invalid and void.
1 620.6009. 1. There is hereby established the
2 "Innovation District Public Safety Fund" for the purpose of
3 reinvesting a portion of net new state economic activity
4 generated within an innovation district into public safety,
5 public infrastructure, and related improvements that support
6 sustained district vitality.
7 2. (1) Subject to the exclusions set forth in this
8 section, the innovation district public safety fund shall
9 receive fifty percent of incremental state tax receipts
10 generated within a designated innovation district that would
11 otherwise be deposited into the state general revenue fund.
12 (2) For purposes of this section, "incremental state
13 tax receipts" means:
14 (a) State sales tax revenues attributable to
15 transactions occurring within the innovation district, in
16 excess of the applicable baseline under subsection 3 of this
17 section; and

SB 1668 18
18 (b) State income tax withholdings attributable to
19 wages paid for employment occurring within the innovation
20 district, in excess of the applicable baseline under
21 subsection 3 of this section.
22 No other state taxes shall be subject to recapture under
23 this section unless expressly authorized by law.
24 3. The baseline for determining incremental state tax
25 receipts shall be established by the administrator based on
26 actual state sales tax and state withholding tax collections
27 within the innovation district during the twelve months
28 immediately preceding designation of the district. The
29 baseline shall remain fixed for the purposes of calculating
30 incremental receipts under this section.
31 4. (1) This section shall not apply to any geographic
32 area located within:
33 (a) A district designated as a super tax increment
34 financing district, whether such a district exists at the
35 time of innovation district designation or is created
36 thereafter; or
37 (b) A district designated under the Missouri Downtown
38 Economic Stimulus Authority Act (MODESA), whether such a
39 district exists at the time of innovation district
40 designation or is created thereafter.
41 (2) Incremental state tax receipts generated within
42 excluded geographic areas shall not be subject to recapture
43 under this section.
44 (3) Excluded geographic areas shall not receive,
45 directly or indirectly, or benefit from moneys remitted to
46 or expended from the innovation district public safety fund,
47 including funding for public safety, infrastructure, or
48 public realm improvements.

SB 1668 19
49 5. (1) Moneys remitted under this section shall be
50 deposited into a dedicated local fund or account established
51 by the participating city for the applicable innovation
52 district.
53 (2) The innovation district board shall have authority
54 to allocate and direct the use of such moneys, subject to
55 the eligible uses set forth in sections 620.6000 to 620.6024
56 and consistent with the innovation district master plan.
57 (3) Moneys remitted under this section shall be used
58 solely for the benefit of the innovation district from which
59 such revenues were generated.
60 (4) All moneys remitted and expended under this
61 section shall remain subject to generally applicable state
62 and local accounting, auditing, and public finance laws.
63 6. (1) Moneys remitted from the innovation district
64 public safety fund may be used for capital or operating
65 expenditures related to public safety and public realm
66 improvements within the innovation district, including but
67 not limited to:
68 (a) Police services and law enforcement staffing;
69 (b) Lighting, cameras, and surveillance systems;
70 (c) Wayfinding and signage;
71 (d) Sidewalks, streets, crosswalks, and traffic-
72 calming improvements;
73 (e) Landscaping, trees, and plazas;
74 (f) Stabilization, remediation, demolition, or
75 redevelopment preparation of real property;
76 (g) Maintenance or operations directly related to
77 public safety or district infrastructure;
78 (h) Other public safety or public infrastructure
79 improvements consistent with the purposes of this section.

SB 1668 20
80 (2) The use of innovation district public safety fund
81 moneys for police services shall be limited to sworn law
82 enforcement officers or duly authorized law enforcement
83 agencies and shall not include private security or non-law-
84 enforcement personnel acting in a public safety capacity.
85 Moneys remitted under this section shall supplement and not
86 supplant existing public safety funding obligations of the
87 participating city.
88 7. (1) A project sponsor may apply to the department
89 of economic development for a construction-phase withholding
90 for a project located within an innovation district,
91 provided that:
92 (a) The project has received all required local
93 approvals; and
94 (b) The project has total hard construction costs of
95 not less than five million dollars.
96 (2) An application for a construction-phase
97 withholding advance shall be submitted to the department
98 after project approval and prior to project stabilization,
99 in such form and manner as prescribed by rule.
100 (3) The department shall authorize a construction-
101 phase withholding advance upon demonstration by the project
102 sponsor that:
103 (a) The project is located within a designated
104 innovation district;
105 (b) The project will generate construction-phase
106 employment occurring within the district; and
107 (c) The project is reasonably projected to generate
108 state income tax withholdings attributable to construction-
109 phase employment above the applicable baseline.

SB 1668 21
110 The department's review shall be limited to verification of
111 eligibility and projected withholding amounts and shall not
112 include discretionary policy evaluation.
113 (4) The amount of a construction-phase withholding
114 advance authorized under this section shall not exceed
115 twenty-five percent of the projected state income tax
116 withholdings attributable to construction-phase employment
117 generated by the project above the applicable baseline. In
118 no event shall a project sponsor receive construction-phase
119 withholding advances exceeding twenty-five percent of actual
120 construction-phase withholdings generated by the project.
121 Construction-phase withholding advances shall not be
122 eligible for use as qualifying reinvestment expenditures
123 under section 620.6015.
124 8. An authorized construction-phase withholding
125 advance shall not be disbursed until the project sponsor
126 demonstrates to the department that:
127 (1) Construction has commenced; and
128 (2) Not less than ten percent of the total hard
129 construction costs have been incurred.
130 Upon satisfaction of such requirements, the department shall
131 disburse the approved advance within forty-five calendar
132 days, as a lump sum.
133 9. The department shall approve or deny an application
134 for a construction-phase withholding advance within forty-
135 five calendar days of receipt of a complete application.
136 Failure to act within such period shall result in deemed
137 approval of the application as submitted.
138 10. For purposes of this section, "construction-phase
139 employment" means employment primarily engaged in
140 construction, demolition, rehabilitation, or related

SB 1668 22
141 activities associated with an approved development project
142 and occurring prior to project stabilization. Construction-
143 phase employment shall not include permanent or stabilized
144 employment.
145 11. (1) Following completion of construction, the
146 department shall verify the actual amount of state income
147 tax withholdings attributable to construction-phase
148 employment generated by the project above the applicable
149 baseline.
150 (2) If twenty-five percent of the actual construction-
151 phase withholdings equals or exceeds the amount of the
152 construction-phase withholding advance disbursed to the
153 project, no further action shall be required.
154 (3) If twenty-five percent of the actual construction-
155 phase withholdings is less than the amount of the
156 construction-phase withholding advance disbursed, the excess
157 shall be repaid by the project sponsor or offset against
158 future allocations, as determined by rule.
159 12. All incremental state tax receipts attributable to
160 construction-phase employment not subject to an approved
161 construction-phase withholding advance shall be allocated
162 for the benefit of the applicable innovation district and
163 controlled by the innovation district board in accordance
164 with sections 620.6000 to 620.6024.
165 13. The department of economic development shall
166 promulgate all rules necessary to implement this section,
167 provided that such rules are consistent with and reasonably
168 necessary to carry out the purposes, structure, and
169 operative provisions of sections 620.6000 to 620.6024. In
170 promulgating such rules, the department shall consult with
171 the department of revenue to the extent necessary for the
172 administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a

SB 1668 23
173 rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is
174 created under the authority delegated in this section shall
175 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
176 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable,
177 section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are
178 nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the
179 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay
180 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
181 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
182 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
183 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
1 620.6012. 1. This section establishes an income tax
2 abatement incentive for qualifying individuals establishing
3 residency within an innovation district.
4 2. As used in this section, the following terms mean:
5 (1) "Primary residence", a dwelling unit within an
6 innovation district that the individual occupies as the
7 individual's principal place of residence for Missouri
8 income tax purposes, whether such dwelling unit is owned or
9 leased by the individual;
10 (2) "Qualified new resident", an individual who:
11 (a) Was not a resident of the state of Missouri for
12 state income tax purposes during the most recent tax year
13 preceding the tax year for which the exclusion is claimed;
14 and
15 (b) Establishes a primary residence within an
16 innovation district and is a resident of the state of
17 Missouri for state income tax purposes during the tax year
18 for which the exclusion is claimed.
19 3. For all tax years beginning on or after January 1,
20 2027, the income tax exclusion authorized by this section
21 shall apply for each tax year in which the individual

SB 1668 24
22 remains a resident of the state of Missouri for income tax
23 purposes and maintains a primary residence within an
24 innovation district. The exclusion shall not apply for any
25 tax year in which either condition is not satisfied.
26 4. Nothing in this section shall be construed to
27 require that a qualified new resident occupy a primary
28 residence within an innovation district for any minimum
29 number of days or months during a tax year, provided the
30 individual otherwise qualifies as a Missouri resident for
31 income tax purposes and maintains such residence as the
32 individual's primary residence.
33 5. Any reduction in tax as a result of such exclusion
34 shall be fully recaptured by the department of revenue for
35 the tax year in which eligibility is lost if the qualified
36 new resident no longer meets the requirements provided under
37 this section. The amount required to be recaptured shall be
38 deemed an underpayment of tax and shall be due and payable
39 on the tax return that is due immediately following the loss
40 of residency.
41 6. Notwithstanding any other limitation contained in
42 the laws of this state, collection of any taxes deemed to be
43 an underpayment by this section shall be allowed for a
44 innovation district of three years following the due date of
45 the recaptured taxes.
46 7. An individual who was a resident of the state of
47 Missouri for income tax purposes during the most recent tax
48 year preceding the tax year for which the exclusion is
49 claimed shall not be eligible for the exclusion authorized
50 by this section.
51 8. The department of economic development shall
52 promulgate all rules necessary to implement this section,
53 provided that such rules are consistent with and reasonably

SB 1668 25
54 necessary to carry out the purposes, structure, and
55 operative provisions of sections 620.6000 to 620.6024. In
56 promulgating such rules, the department shall consult with
57 the department of revenue to the extent necessary for the
58 administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a
59 rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is
60 created under the authority delegated in this section shall
61 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
62 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable,
63 section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are
64 nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the
65 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay
66 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
67 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
68 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
69 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
70 9. Under section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
71 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under
72 this section shall sunset ten years after the effective date
73 of this section unless reauthorized by an act of the general
74 assembly; and
75 (2) This section shall terminate on September first of
76 the calendar year immediately following the calendar year in
