1 620.6015. 1. This section establishes an employer
2 retention and reinvestment withholding incentive for
3 retention of jobs and reinvestment by businesses
4 establishing a continuous presence in an innovation district.
5 2. As used in this section, the following terms mean:
6 (1) "Baseline payroll", the employer's average
7 quarterly gross payroll attributable to the innovation
8 district location for the four consecutive calendar quarters

SB 1668 26
9 immediately preceding approval of a withholding agreement
10 under this section, or such alternative baseline as may be
11 established for a newly locating or expanding employer under
12 a withholding agreement;
13 (2) "Eligible employee", an employee whose primary
14 work location is physically located within the innovation
15 district and who performs services on-site at such location
16 on a regular basis;
17 (3) "Eligible employer", an employer that operates a
18 business within an innovation district and that satisfies
19 the requirements of this section. An eligible employer
20 shall not include an employer that relocates, consolidates,
21 or transfers business operations from a location outside the
22 innovation district to a location within the district if
23 such relocation results in a material reduction of payroll
24 at the originating location;
25 (4) "Material reduction of payroll", a reduction of
26 more than five percent in the employer's aggregate gross
27 payroll attributable to the originating location, as
28 compared to the applicable baseline payroll;
29 (5) "Qualifying reinvestment expenditures" or "QREs",
30 documented expenditures incurred by an eligible employer for
31 capital improvements or other investments at or for the
32 benefit of the innovation district location, including but
33 not limited to: security and safety improvements, including
34 security officers, lighting, cameras, and access control;
35 building systems improvements; tenant improvements; public
36 infrastructure improvements; life-safety systems; code
37 compliance; accessibility improvements; or other
38 expenditures approved by the department that are consistent
39 with the purposes of this section, provided that such

SB 1668 27
40 expenditures supplement and do not supplant ordinary
41 operating expenses;
42 (6) "Withholding agreement", a written agreement
43 entered into between an eligible employer and the department
44 of economic development under this section that specifies:
45 (a) The amount and duration of the withholding benefit;
46 (b) The method by which the withholding benefit is
47 delivered, whether as a credit or authorized retention of
48 withholdings;
49 (c) The qualifying reinvestment expenditures to be
50 undertaken by the employer, demonstrating that the QREs
51 supplant existing operating or capital expenditures;
52 (d) Payroll baseline and maintenance requirements;
53 (e) Reporting, verification, audit, notice, and cure
54 requirements; and
55 (f) Any other terms necessary to carry out the
56 purposes of this section;
57 (7) "Withholding benefit", the state income tax
58 withholdings attributable to eligible employees that an
59 eligible employer is authorized to receive, either through a
60 credit or through authorized retention of such withholdings,
61 which may be carried forward under a withholding agreement
62 under this section;
63 (8) "Withholding tax credit", a nonrefundable credit
64 against the employer's liability otherwise due under chapter
65 143, equal to all or a portion of the withholding benefit
66 authorized under a withholding agreement under this section,
67 which may be carried forward in accordance with this section.
68 3. An eligible employer may, but shall not be required
69 to, apply to enter into a withholding agreement with the
70 department of economic development under this section. For
71 all tax years beginning on or after January 1, 2027, an

SB 1668 28
72 eligible employer that enters into a withholding agreement
73 may receive a withholding benefit attributable to eligible
74 employees. The withholding benefit may be delivered either
75 as a withholding tax credit or as authorized retention of
76 state income tax withholdings, as specified in the
77 withholding agreement. The method of delivery shall not
78 affect the amount of the withholding benefit authorized
79 under this section.
80 4. (1) Applications for a withholding agreement may
81 be submitted at any time. The department of economic
82 development shall approve or deny any application for a
83 withholding agreement within forty-five calendar days of
84 receipt of a complete application. The department shall
85 approve a withholding agreement unless it determines that:
86 (a) The applicant does not meet the eligibility
87 requirements of this section; or
88 (b) The applicant is not in good standing with the
89 department of economic development or the department of
90 revenue with respect to tax compliance or reporting
91 obligations.
92 (2) Any denial shall be issued in writing and shall
93 state the specific grounds for denial. Failure of the
94 department to approve or deny an application within forty-
95 five calendar days shall result in approval of the
96 application as submitted.
97 5. The withholding benefit authorized under this
98 section shall not exceed three percent of the aggregate
99 gross wages paid to eligible employees at the innovation
100 district location during a tax year. The withholding
101 benefit may be authorized for an innovation district not to
102 exceed ten years, as specified in the withholding
103 agreement. A withholding tax credit issued under this

SB 1668 29
104 section shall be nonrefundable and may be carried forward in
105 accordance with the terms of the withholding agreement. The
106 department may establish aggregate or annual program caps by
107 rule to manage fiscal exposure.
108 6. A withholding agreement shall provide that the
109 withholding benefit is requested and authorized on a
110 quarterly basis, based on state income tax withholdings
111 attributable to covered employees during the applicable
112 calendar quarter. The department of economic development
113 may authorize a withholding agreement to permit requests on
114 a semi-annual basis, if determined appropriate based on the
115 size or nature of the employer and provided that such
116 authorization does not impart verification or compliance.
117 In no event shall a withholding agreement authorize
118 automatic retention or crediting of withholdings beyond the
119 applicable request period without review and verification as
120 required by this section.
121 7. Any withholding benefit received under this section
122 shall be used solely for qualifying reinvestment
123 expenditures. In no event shall the total amount of
124 withholding benefit received by an eligible employer exceed
125 the total amount of qualifying reinvestment expenditures
126 actually incurred and paid under the withholding agreement.
127 8. To receive and retain a withholding benefit under
128 this section, an eligible employer shall:
129 (1) Operate within an innovation district;
130 (2) Demonstrate a commitment to remain at the
131 innovation district location for not less than five years;
132 (3) Complete qualifying reinvestment expenditures
133 under the withholding agreement;
134 (4) Maintain not less than ninety-five percent of
135 baseline payroll, subject to notice and cure; and

SB 1668 30
136 (5) Submit any other information reasonably requested
137 by the department.
138 9. (1) An employer receiving a withholding benefit
139 shall submit to the department of economic development, on a
140 quarterly basis, a certification of:
141 (a) State income tax withholdings attributable to
142 eligible employees;
143 (b) Compliance with payroll maintenance requirements;
144 and
145 (c) Qualifying reinvestment expenditures incurred to
146 date.
147 (2) If the department determines that an employer is
148 not in compliance, the department shall provide written
149 notice of noncompliance. The employer shall have thirty
150 calendar days from receipt of such notice to cure the
151 noncompliance or submit a cure plan acceptable to the
152 department. If the employer fails to cure within the
153 applicable innovation district, the withholding agreement
154 may be suspended or terminated, and any excess withholding
155 benefit shall be subject to recapture as provided in the
156 agreement.
157 10. The department may authorize a withholding
158 agreement for an employer that is newly locating or
159 expanding within an innovation district, provided that
160 baseline payroll is established under the withholding
161 agreement following a reasonable ramp-up innovation district.
162 11. The department of economic development may audit
163 QREs and withholding benefit usage. Any amount determined
164 to have been improperly claimed or retained shall be repaid
165 to the state or offset against future withholding benefits,
166 as provided in the withholding agreement.

SB 1668 31
167 12. An employer may participate in the incentive
168 authorized under this section concurrently with
169 participation in the Missouri one start program under
170 sections 620.800 to 620.809, the Missouri quality jobs act
171 under sections 620.1875 to 620.1890, or the state economic
172 development programs, provided that each program's statutory
173 requirements are independently satisfied. Participation
174 under this section shall not disqualify an employer from
175 other incentives, nor shall benefits under this section be
176 aggregated for purposes of determining eligibility or
177 leverage under other programs expressly required by law.
178 The withholding tax credit under the Missouri one start
179 program under sections 620.800 to 620.809 or the Missouri
180 quality jobs act under sections 620.1875 to 620.1890 shall
181 be collected and disbursed prior to the collection and
182 disbursement of the withholding benefits under the
183 provisions of this section.
184 13. Tax credits issued under the provisions of this
185 section shall not be refundable. No tax credit claimed
186 under this section shall be assigned, transferred, sold, or
187 otherwise conveyed.
188 14. The department of economic development, in
189 coordination with the department of revenue, shall
190 promulgate all necessary rules and regulations for the
191 administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a
192 rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is
193 created under the authority delegated in this section shall
194 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
195 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable,
196 section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are
197 nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the
198 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay

SB 1668 32
199 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
200 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
201 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
202 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
203 15. Under section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
204 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under
205 this section shall sunset ten years after the effective date
206 of this section unless reauthorized by an act of the general
207 assembly;
208 (2) This section shall terminate on September first of
