1 620.6018. 1. This section establishes an employer
2 relocation withholding tax credit incentive.
3 2. As used in this section, the following terms mean:
4 (1) "Eligible employee", an individual who:
5 (a) Relocates from a location outside the state of
6 Missouri to accept employment with an eligible employer;
7 (b) Establishes a primary residence within an
8 innovation district or a location within ten miles of an
9 innovation district, measured in a straight-line distance,
10 provided such residence is located within the state of
11 Missouri; and
12 (c) Earns annual wages of at least seventy thousand
13 dollars;
14 (2) "Eligible employer", a business entity that:

SB 1668 33
15 (a) Was not conducting business operations within the
16 state of Missouri prior to establishing operations within an
17 innovation district; and
18 (b) Establishes a business location within an
19 innovation district;
20 (3) "Eligible relocation expenses", includes
21 reasonable and necessary, one-time costs incurred in
22 connection with an eligible employee's relocation to the
23 state of Missouri, which may include:
24 (a) Moving and transportation expenses for household
25 goods and personal effects;
26 (b) Travel expenses associated with the relocation;
27 (c) Temporary housing expenses incurred during the
28 relocation period; and
29 (d) Relocation-related professional services, as
30 further defined by rule of the department of economic
31 development;
32 (4) "Primary residence", a dwelling unit located
33 within the geographic area described in paragraph (b) of
34 subdivision (1) of this subsection that the eligible
35 employee occupies as the employee's principal place of
36 residence for Missouri income tax purposes, whether owned or
37 leased, and that the employee intends to use as such
38 residence during the period required under this section;
39 (5) "State tax credit", a credit against the tax
40 otherwise due under chapter 143 or 148.
41 3. For all tax years beginning on or after January 1,
42 2027, an eligible employer shall be allowed to claim a tax
43 credit against the employer's state tax liability in an
44 amount up to five thousand dollars per tax year per eligible
45 employee for eligible relocation expenses incurred on behalf
46 of such employees.

SB 1668 34
47 4. An eligible employer applying for a state tax
48 credit under the provisions of this section shall follow the
49 application procedures established under section 620.6000
50 and any additional requirements established by the
51 department of economic development. If the employer meets
52 all criteria required under the provisions of this section
53 and section 620.6000 and approval is granted by the
54 department of economic development, the department shall
55 issue a tax credit certificate in the appropriate amount.
56 5. Tax credits issued under the provisions of this
57 section shall be refundable. Tax credits claimed under this
58 section may be carried forward to subsequent tax years up to
59 five years. No tax credit claimed under this section shall
60 be assigned, transferred, sold, or otherwise conveyed.
61 6. State tax credits claimed by an employer under this
62 section shall be recaptured by the department of revenue if
63 the eligible employee relocates to another residence that no
64 longer meets the requirements provided under this section
65 within twelve consecutive months after the state tax credit
66 is claimed. Any amount required to be recaptured shall be
67 due and payable on the tax return that is due immediately
68 following the employee's relocation.
69 7. The department of economic development, in
70 coordination with the department of revenue, shall
71 promulgate all necessary rules and regulations for the
72 administration of this section. Any rule or portion of a
73 rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is
74 created under the authority delegated in this section shall
75 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
76 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable,
77 section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are
78 nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the

SB 1668 35
79 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay
80 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
81 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
82 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
83 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
84 8. Under section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
85 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under
