1 620.6021. 1. This section establishes an office-to-
2 residential conversion tax credit incentive.
3 2. As used in this section, the following terms mean:
4 (1) "Department", the Missouri department of economic
5 development;
6 (2) "Innovation District", the program created under
7 section 620.6000;
8 (3) "Qualified conversion expenditures", any amount
9 properly chargeable to a capital account. The term
10 "qualified conversion expenditures" shall not include:
11 (a) The cost of acquisition;
12 (b) Any expenditure attributable to the enlargement of
13 an existing building; or
14 (c) Tax-exempt properties;

SB 1668 36
15 (4) "Qualified converted building", any building and
16 its structural components if:
17 (a) Prior to conversion, such building was
18 nonresidential real property, as defined in 26 U.S.C.
19 Section 168(e)(2)(B), as amended, that was leased, or
20 available for lease, to office tenants, or utilized for
21 office purposes by the owner-occupant;
22 (b) Such building has been substantially converted
23 from an office use to a predominantly residential use,
24 defined as more than fifty percent of the gross square
25 footage of the building, and may also include retail, or
26 other commercial use, and may also include accessory on-site
27 or required off-site parking;
28 (c) Such building was initially placed in service at
29 least twenty-five years before the beginning of the
30 conversion; and
31 (d) Such building was vacant or blighted and has been
32 substantially converted from office use to residential or
33 mixed-use;
34 (5) "Substantially converted", qualified conversion
35 expenditures incurred during the twenty-four-month period
36 preceding final approval of tax credits that in total are
37 greater than:
38 (a) The adjusted basis of such building and its
39 structural components, as determined as of the beginning of
40 the first day of such twenty-four-month period, or of the
41 holding period of the building, whichever is later; or
42 (b) Fifteen thousand dollars if the property is
43 located in a qualified Missouri main street district, or
44 five hundred thousand dollars if the property is not located
45 in a qualified Missouri main street district. In the case
46 of any conversion that may reasonably be expected to be

SB 1668 37
47 completed in phases set forth in architectural plans and
48 specifications completed before the conversion begins,
49 qualified conversion expenditures shall be totaled for the
50 sixty-month period preceding final approval of tax credits
51 rather than the twenty-four-month period preceding such
52 final approval;
53 (6) "Tax credit", the office-to-residential conversion
54 tax credit authorized by this section, which may be applied,
55 at the election of the taxpayer, against:
56 (a) The taxpayer's liability under chapter 143; or
57 (b) The taxpayer's liability for state sales and use
58 taxes under chapter 144;
59 (7) "Upper-floor housing", any housing that is
60 attached to or contained in the same building as commercial
61 property, whether located on the ground floor behind the
62 traditional storefront or on other floors of the property.
63 3. (1) For all tax years beginning on or after
64 January 1, 2027, the department shall issue a taxpayer a tax
65 credit up to twenty-five percent of qualified conversion
66 expenditures with respect to a qualified converted building
67 or upper-floor housing located in a qualified innovation
68 district. If the amount of such tax credit exceeds the
69 taxpayer's state tax liability for the year in which tax
70 credits are issued, the amount that exceeds the state tax
71 liability may be carried back to any of the three preceding
72 tax years or carried forward for credit against state tax
73 liability for the succeeding ten tax years, or until the
74 full credit is used, whichever occurs first.
75 (2) Tax credits authorized under this section may be
76 transferred, sold, or assigned, and shall retain the same
77 attributes as in the hands of the assignor. Tax credits may
78 be transferred multiple times. In order to transfer a tax

SB 1668 38
79 credit authorized under this section, the assignor and
80 assignee shall complete and submit a tax credit transfer
81 form provided by the department of revenue. Such transfers
82 may be facilitated through an intermediary entity as
83 permitted by law without affecting the nature or attributes
84 of the tax credit.
85 (3) Tax credits authorized for a partnership, a
86 limited liability company taxed as a partnership, or
87 multiple owners of property shall be passed through to the
88 partners, members, or owners respectively pro rata, or under
89 an executed agreement among the partners, members, or owners
90 documenting an alternate distribution method.
91 (4) The assignee of a tax credit may use the acquired
92 tax credits to offset up to one hundred percent of the
93 taxpayer's state tax liability. The assignor shall perfect
94 such transfer by notifying the department in writing within
95 thirty calendar days following the effective date of the
96 transfer and shall provide any information as may reasonably
97 be required by the department.
98 4. (1) For all tax years beginning on or after
99 January 1, 2027, the department shall issue a taxpayer a tax
100 credit up to thirty percent of qualified conversion
101 expenditures with respect to upper-floor housing located in
102 a qualified Missouri main street district. If the amount of
103 such tax credit exceeds the taxpayer's state tax liability
104 for the year in which tax credits are issued, the amount
105 that exceeds the state tax liability may be carried back to
106 any of the three preceding tax years or carried forward for
107 credit against state tax liability for the succeeding ten
108 tax years, or until the full credit is used, whichever
109 occurs first.

SB 1668 39
110 (2) Tax credits authorized under this section may be
111 transferred, sold, or assigned, and shall retain the same
112 attributes as in the hands of the assignor. Tax credits may
113 be transferred multiple times. In order to transfer a tax
114 credit authorized under this section, the assignor and
115 assignee shall complete and submit a tax credit transfer
116 form provided by the department of revenue. Such transfers
117 may be facilitated through an intermediary entity as
118 permitted by law without affecting the nature or attributes
119 of the tax credit.
120 (3) Tax credits authorized for a partnership, a
121 limited liability company taxed as a partnership, or
122 multiple owners of property shall be passed through to the
123 partners, members, or owners respectively pro rata, or under
124 an executed agreement among the partners, members, or owners
125 documenting an alternate distribution method.
126 (4) The assignee of a tax credit may use the acquired
127 tax credits to offset up to one hundred percent of the
128 taxpayer's state tax liability. The assignor shall perfect
129 such transfer by notifying the department in writing within
130 thirty calendar days following the effective date of the
131 transfer and shall provide any information as may be
132 required by the department.
133 5. (1) The total amount of tax credits authorized
134 under this section shall not exceed fifty million dollars in
135 any fiscal year.
136 (2) Fifty percent of the maximum amount of tax credits
137 available to be authorized to taxpayers in a fiscal year
138 under this section shall be authorized solely for structures
139 of more than seven hundred fifty thousand gross square
140 feet. If the total amount of such reserved tax credits has
141 been authorized, structures of more than seven hundred fifty

SB 1668 40
142 thousand gross square feet may receive tax credits from the
143 remaining unreserved amount of tax credits. If the total
144 amount of reserved tax credits has not been authorized by
145 the department, structures of less than seven hundred fifty
146 thousand gross square feet may be authorized to receive tax
147 credits from such reserved amount. The total amount of tax
148 credits for a structure of more than seven hundred fifty
149 thousand gross square feet may be allocated to the annual
150 limits provided in this section over a period of up to ten
151 years if:
152 (a) The project otherwise meets all the requirements
153 of this section and section 620.6000; and
154 (b) The project meets the ten percent incurred costs
155 test under this section within thirty-six months after an
156 award is authorized.
157 Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require
158 allocation over multiple tax years where sufficient annual
159 capacity exists.
160 (3) Twenty-five percent of the maximum amount of tax
161 credits available to be authorized to taxpayers in a fiscal
162 year under this section shall be authorized solely for upper-
163 floor housing projects located in a qualified Missouri main
164 street district. If the total amount of such reserved tax
165 credits have been authorized, upper-floor housing projects
166 located in a qualified Missouri main street district may
167 receive tax credits from the remaining unreserved amount of
168 tax credits. If the total amount of reserved tax credits
169 has not been authorized by the department, projects not
170 located in a qualified Missouri main street district may be
171 authorized tax credits from such reserved amount.

SB 1668 41
172 (4) If the maximum amount of tax credits allowed in
173 any fiscal year, as provided under this section, is
174 authorized, the maximum amount of tax credits allowed under
175 this section shall be adjusted by the percentage increase in
176 the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers, or its
177 successor index, as such index is defined and officially
178 reported by the United States Department of Labor, or its
179 successor agency, beginning in the fiscal year following any
180 fiscal year in which the full annual cap is authorized.
181 Only one such adjustment shall be made for each instance in
