198 allocation of tax credits becomes available for approval.
199 7. (1) To obtain approval for tax credits under this
200 section, a taxpayer shall submit to the department an
201 application for preliminary approval for tax credit
202 authorization. The department shall have sixty calendar
203 days to review the application and shall notify the

SB 1668 42
204 applicant in writing within thirty calendar days of the
205 decision of whether the application has been authorized for
206 tax credits. Each application for approval, including any
207 applications received for supplemental allocations of tax
208 credits, as provided under this section, shall be authorized
209 for tax credits in the order of submission.
210 (2) Each application shall be reviewed by the
211 department for approval. In order to receive approval, an
212 application shall include:
213 (a) Proof of ownership or site control. Proof of
214 ownership shall include evidence that the taxpayer is the
215 fee simple owner of the eligible property, such as a
216 warranty deed or a closing statement. Proof of site control
217 may be evidenced by a leasehold interest or an option to
218 acquire such an interest. If the taxpayer is in the process
219 of acquiring fee simple ownership, proof of site control
220 shall include an executed sales contract or an executed
221 option to purchase the eligible property;
222 (b) Floor plans of the existing structure,
223 architectural plans and, where applicable, plans of the
224 proposed conversion of the structure, as well as proposed
225 additions;
226 (c) The estimated cost of conversion, the anticipated
227 total costs of the project, the actual basis of the
228 property, as shown by proof of actual acquisition costs, the
229 anticipated total labor costs, the estimated project start
230 date, and the estimated project completion date;
231 (d) Proof that the property is an eligible property;
232 (e) A copy of all land use and building approvals
233 reasonably necessary for the commencement of the project; and

SB 1668 43
234 (f) Any other information that the department may
235 reasonably require to review the project for approval to
236 determine compliance with the requirements of this section.
237 8. Only the property for which a property address is
238 provided in the application shall be reviewed for approval.
239 Once selected for review, a taxpayer shall not be permitted
240 to request the review of another property for approval in
241 the place of the property contained in such application.
242 Any disapproved application shall be removed from the review
243 process. If an application is removed from the review
244 process, the department shall notify the taxpayer in writing
245 of the decision to remove such application. The taxpayer
246 may subsequently submit a revised application. For the
247 purposes of determining the order of submission and
248 authorization of credits, the revised application shall be
249 considered a new application.
250 9. The department shall use the innovation district
251 master scorecard under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024 for the
252 approval of the proposed project and to determine the credit
253 amount. The applicant shall receive a score of at least
254 fifty points to qualify for the lowest tier of incentive,
255 which is a ten percent credit.
256 10. If the department determines that the application
257 meets the requirements of this section and section 620.6000
258 to receive an authorization of tax credits, the taxpayer
259 shall be notified in writing within forty-five days of the
260 approval for an amount of tax credits equal to the amounts
261 provided in this section, subject to the provisions of
262 section 620.6000, unless approval of such credits would
263 cause the total aggregate amount of tax credits approved
264 under this section for all projects in the applicable tax
265 year to exceed the annual limitation established herein.

SB 1668 44
266 Tax credits approved under this section shall be approved
267 and administered independently of any other state tax credit
268 program and shall not be aggregated or evaluated in
269 combination with other state tax credits for purposes of
270 determining eligibility, scoring, leverage ratios, or
271 maximum award limitations under such other programs. Such
272 approvals shall be granted to applications in the order of
273 priority established under this section and shall require
274 full compliance thereafter with all other requirements of
275 law as a condition to any claim for such tax credits.
276 11. Following approval of an application, the identity
277 of the taxpayer contained in such application shall not be
278 modified except:
279 (1) The taxpayer may add partners, members, or
280 shareholders as part of the ownership structure, so long as
281 the principal remains the same; provided, however, that
282 subsequent to the commencement of renovation and the
283 expenditure of at least ten percent of the proposed
284 rehabilitation budget, removal of the principal for failure
285 to perform duties and the appointment of a new principal
286 thereafter shall not constitute a change of the principal; or
287 (2) Where the ownership of the project is changed due
288 to a foreclosure, deed in lieu of a foreclosure or voluntary
289 conveyance, or a transfer in bankruptcy.
290 12. Upon approval of a tax credit application, a
291 taxpayer shall:
292 (1) Submit within one hundred twenty days from the
293 date of the award of such credits, evidence of the capacity
294 of the applicant to finance the costs and expenses for the
295 conversion of the eligible property in the form of a line of
296 credit or letter of commitment subject to the lender's
297 termination for a material adverse change impacting the

SB 1668 45
298 extension of credit. If the department determines that a
299 taxpayer has failed to comply with the requirements of this
300 subdivision, the department shall notify the applicant of
301 such failure and the applicant shall have a thirty-day
302 period from the date of such notice to submit additional
303 evidence to remedy the failure; and
304 (2) Commence conversion within twelve months of the
305 date of issuance of the letter from the department granting
306 the approval for tax credits. For the purposes of this
307 subsection, "commence conversion" shall mean that, as of the
308 date in which actual physical work, contemplated by the
309 architectural plans submitted with the application, has
310 begun, the taxpayer has incurred no less than ten percent of
311 the estimated hard construction costs provided in the
312 application. Taxpayers with approval of a project shall
313 submit evidence of compliance with the provisions of this
314 subsection. If the department determines that a taxpayer
315 has failed to comply with the requirements of this
316 subdivision, the department shall provide the taxpayer
317 written notice of noncompliance. The taxpayer shall have
318 thirty calendar days from receipt of such notice to respond
319 in writing to the department and demonstrate that conversion
320 has commenced, substantial steps toward commencement have
321 been taken, or good cause exists for the delay. Upon a
322 showing of good cause, including delays beyond the
323 taxpayer's reasonable control, the department shall grant a
324 cure period of not less than ninety calendar days to allow
325 commencement of conversion. Tax credits approved under this
326 section shall be rescinded only if the taxpayer fails to
327 commence conversion within the applicable period following
328 written notice and opportunity to cure. Rescinded tax
329 credits shall be included in the total amount of tax credits

SB 1668 46
330 from which approvals may be granted. In such a case, the
331 applicant may submit a new application for the project.
332 13. To claim a tax credit authorized under this
333 section, a taxpayer with approval shall apply for final
334 approval and issuance of tax credits from the department,
335 which shall determine the final amount of qualified
336 conversion expenditures and whether the project meets the
337 requirements of this section. A taxpayer shall submit to
338 the department a final application demonstrating:
339 (1) That the taxpayer has substantially converted a
340 qualified converted building or upper-floor housing;
341 (2) Satisfactory evidence of any qualified conversion
342 expenditures for the structure, as determined by the
343 department; and
344 (3) Any other information reasonably requested by the
345 department to verify qualified conversion expenditures or
346 compliance with the requirements of this section or section
347 620.6000.
348 14. For financial institutions, tax credits authorized
349 under this section shall be deemed to be redevelopment tax
350 credits for the purposes of sections 135.800 to 135.830.
351 The approval of all applications and the issuing of
352 certificates of eligible tax credits to taxpayers shall be
353 performed by the department. The department shall inform a
354 taxpayer of final approval by letter and shall issue to the
355 taxpayer tax credit certificates. The taxpayer shall attach
356 the certificate to all Missouri tax returns on which the
357 credit is claimed.
358 15. (1) The department shall issue seventy-five
359 percent of the approved tax credits under this section
360 within forty-five calendar days of receiving all required
361 final application materials. Within ninety calendar days of

SB 1668 47
362 receiving all required final application materials, the
363 department shall make a final determination of costs and
364 issue the remaining twenty-five percent of approved tax
365 credits, or request repayment from the applicant if the
366 final determination results in an over-issuance of tax
367 credits. In the event the amount of qualified conversion
368 expenditures incurred by a taxpayer would result in the
369 issuance of an amount of tax credits in excess of the amount
370 authorized under this section, such taxpayer may apply to
371 the department for issuance of tax credits in an amount
372 equal to such excess. Applications for issuance of tax
373 credits in excess of the amount provided under a taxpayer's
374 application shall be made on a form prescribed by the
375 department. Such applications shall be subject to all
376 provisions regarding priority provided under this section.
377 (2) For tax credits authorized under this section, the
378 applicant may submit to the department an application for
379 the issuance of tax credits annually prior to final
380 completion of the project. Upon approval of the annual
381 application for issuance, the department shall issue eighty
382 percent of the amount of tax credits that would result from
383 the qualified conversion expenditures, provided the total
384 amount of credits issued to date does not exceed the total
385 amount of credits authorized for the project to date. Any
386 remaining authorized tax credits shall be issued upon the
387 final approval of the project. The department shall issue
388 eighty percent of the approved credits within forty-five
389 calendar days of receiving all required application
390 materials. Within ninety calendar days of receiving all
391 required application materials, the department shall make a
392 final determination of costs and issue any remaining
393 authorized tax credits upon the final completion of the

SB 1668 48
394 phased project, or request repayment if an over-issuance of
395 credits is determined.
396 16. No taxpayer shall be issued tax credits for
397 qualified conversion expenditures on a qualified converted
398 building within twenty-seven years of a previous issuance of
399 tax credits under this section on such qualified converted
400 buildings.
401 17. The department, in coordination with the
402 department of revenue, shall promulgate all necessary rules
403 and regulations to administer the provisions of this
404 section. Any rule or portion of a rule, as that term is
405 defined in section 536.010, that is created under the
406 authority delegated in this section shall become effective
407 only if it complies with and is subject to all of the
408 provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable, section
409 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are nonseverable and
410 if any of the powers vested with the general assembly
411 pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay the effective
412 date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are subsequently
413 held unconstitutional, then the grant of rulemaking
414 authority and any rule proposed or adopted after August 28,
415 2026, shall be invalid and void.
416 18. Under section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
417 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under
418 this section shall sunset ten years after the effective date
419 of this section unless reauthorized by an act of the general
420 assembly;
421 (2) This section shall terminate on September first of
422 the calendar year immediately following the calendar year in
423 which the program authorized under this section is sunset;
424 and

SB 1668 49
425 (3) The provisions of this subsection shall not be
426 construed to limit or in any way impair:
427 (a) A taxpayer's ability to complete a project and
428 receive authorization for tax credits for any project for
429 which the taxpayer has submitted an initial application on
430 or before the date the program authorized under this section
431 expires; or
432 (b) The department of revenue's ability to redeem tax
433 credits authorized on or before the date the program
434 authorized under this section expires, or a taxpayer's
435 ability to redeem such tax credits.
1 620.6024. 1. This section establishes a "Missouri
2 Opportunity Zone", an overlay of the innovation district, to
3 encourage long-term private investment in innovation
4 districts by allowing the deferral and potential exclusion
5 of Missouri income tax liabilities when such amounts are
6 reinvested into qualifying property or businesses located
7 within such districts.
8 2. For purposes of this section, the following terms
9 mean:
10 (1) "Equity investment", an ownership interest in an
11 operating business or investment property, whether held
12 directly or indirectly, including as a general partner,
13 limited partner, member, or shareholder, that is subject to
14 the risks of the enterprise and does not constitute
15 indebtedness or a loan obligation;
16 (2) "Inclusion event", any event that terminates or
17 partially terminates deferral under this section, as set
18 forth in subsection 4 of this section;
19 (3) "Innovation district", a district designated under
20 sections 620.6000 to 620.6024;

SB 1668 50
21 (4) "Investment property", real property located
22 within a Missouri opportunity zone that is acquired, held,
23 or improved for purposes of commercial, residential, or
24 mixed-use investment, whether or not such property is income-
25 producing or cash-flowing at the time of acquisition, and
26 that is not treated as an operating business for purposes of
27 this section;
28 (5) "Missouri income tax liability", Missouri income
29 tax otherwise due under chapter 143 for a tax year;
30 (6) "Missouri opportunity zone", any innovation
31 district designated under sections 620.6000 to 620.6024
32 within which private capital investment is encouraged
33 through the deferral and potential exclusion of Missouri
34 income tax liabilities when such liabilities are reinvested
35 into qualifying property or operating businesses located
36 within such district;
37 (7) "Operating business", a trade or business that is
38 located within and conducts a substantial portion of its
39 active trade or business operations within a Missouri
40 opportunity zone, including the production of income through
41 the provision of goods or services, employment or personnel,
42 or leasing of space as part of an active business enterprise;
43 (8) "Qualified Missouri opportunity zone fund", an
44 entity organized for the purpose of investing in one or more
45 qualified Missouri opportunity zone investments,
46 substantially all of the assets of which consist of such
47 investments, as measured on the last day of the first six-
48 month period of the fund's tax year and the last day of the
49 fund's tax year, and that is certified or otherwise approved
50 by the department of economic development in accordance with
51 rules promulgated under this section. Use of a qualified

SB 1668 51
52 Missouri opportunity zone fund shall be permitted but not
53 required;
54 (9) "Qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment",
55 an equity investment in:
56 (a) Investment property located within a Missouri
57 opportunity zone; or
58 (b) An operating business that is located within and
59 conducts a substantial portion of its active trade or
60 business operations within a Missouri opportunity zone;
61 (10) "Taxpayer", a person subject to Missouri income
62 tax under chapter 143, including income reported on a pass-
63 through basis by an owner, partner, or member of a
64 partnership, limited liability company, or S corporation.
65 The term "taxpayer" shall not include any entity subject to
66 Missouri corporate income tax, including any C corporation.
67 3. (1) A taxpayer may elect to defer payment of
68 Missouri income tax otherwise due for a tax year if the
69 amount of such Missouri income tax liability is invested, in
70 the manner prescribed by this section, into a qualified
71 Missouri opportunity zone investment.
72 (2) The deferral authorized by this subsection shall
73 apply to ordinary Missouri income tax liabilities.
74 (3) Eligibility under this section shall not be
75 conditioned on the residency of the taxpayer, provided that
76 the deferral authorized by this section shall apply only for
77 tax years in which the taxpayer remains subject to Missouri
78 income tax under chapter 143.
79 (4) The election to defer Missouri income tax under
80 this section may be made with respect to all or any portion
81 of a taxpayer's Missouri income tax liability for a tax
82 year, in the manner prescribed by the department of revenue.

SB 1668 52
83 4. To qualify for deferral under this section, a
84 taxpayer shall make a qualified Missouri opportunity zone
85 investment not later than one hundred eighty days after the
86 close of the tax year for which the Missouri income tax
87 liability is otherwise due.
88 5. The deferral of Missouri income tax under this
89 section shall continue until the earliest occurrence of an
90 inclusion event, including:
91 (1) The sale, exchange, or other disposition of the
92 qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment;
93 (2) When the investment ceases to qualify as a
94 qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment;
95 (3) Ten years from the date of the qualified Missouri
96 opportunity zone investment;
97 (4) In the case of an operating business, the failure
98 to commence substantial active trade or business operations
99 within twenty-four months of the initial qualified Missouri
100 opportunity zone investment, as determined by the department
101 of economic development; or
102 (5) (a) In the case of investment property, failure
103 to satisfy the requirements of paragraph (b) of this
104 subdivision.
105 (b) A qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment
106 in investment property shall continue to qualify for
107 deferral under this section so long as one or more of the
108 following conditions is satisfied:
109 a. The investment property is placed into active
110 commercial or residential use, including leasing, occupancy,
111 or other income-producing operation, within thirty months
112 following the qualified Missouri opportunity zone
113 investment; or

SB 1668 53
114 b. Within thirty months of the date of the initial
115 qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment in the
116 investment property, the taxpayer, either directly or
117 through one or more affiliated entities, invests an amount
118 equal to or greater than the adjusted basis of the property,
119 excluding land, in improvements that materially enhance the
120 value, utility, or productive use of the property. For
121 purposes of this subparagraph, the required investment
122 amount may be satisfied through any combination of capital
123 contributions, including amounts attributable to Missouri
124 income tax deferred under this section and other cash or
125 equity contributions invested in the property. Debt
126 financing shall not be treated as an equity investment for
127 purposes of satisfying this test.
128 6. In the case of a qualified Missouri opportunity
129 zone investment, if such operating business or investment
130 property generates net income attributable to the investment
131 during any tax year prior to an inclusion event or the
132 expiration of the deferral period, the amount of Missouri
133 income tax previously deferred under this section shall be
134 included in Missouri taxable income for such tax year in an
135 amount equal to the net income so generated, and any
136 remaining deferred amount shall continue to be deferred in
137 accordance with this section.
138 7. If a taxpayer holds a qualified Missouri
139 opportunity investment for a period of not less than ten
140 years, any gain attributable to such investment and
141 recognized for Missouri income tax purposes upon disposition
142 shall be excluded from Missouri taxable income.
143 8. The Missouri opportunity zone program shall operate
144 independently of federal opportunity zone law.
145 Participation in, qualification for, or designation as a

SB 1668 54
146 federal opportunity zone shall not be required to qualify
147 for benefits under this section.
148 9. The department of revenue and the department of
149 economic development may adopt rules to coordinate benefits
150 under this section with other state tax incentives to
151 prevent the deferral or exclusion of the same Missouri
152 income tax liability from being claimed more than once.
153 10. Notwithstanding the repeal, expiration, or
154 nonrenewal of this section, any taxpayer that has made a
155 qualified Missouri opportunity zone investment prior to such
156 repeal, expiration, or nonrenewal shall remain eligible for
157 the deferral and exclusion benefits provided under this
158 section with respect to such investment, subject to the
159 terms and conditions in effect at the time the investment
160 was made.
161 11. The department of revenue, in consultation with
162 the department of economic development, shall administer
163 this section and may require reasonable documentation to
164 verify:
165 (1) The amount of Missouri income tax deferred;
166 (2) The nature and location of the qualified Missouri
167 opportunity zone investment; and
168 (3) Compliance with the investment timing, active use,
169 capital deployment, holding period, and inclusion-event
170 requirements of this section.
171 12. The department of economic development shall
172 promulgate rules to implement this section. Such rules
173 shall be consistent with and reasonably necessary to carry
174 out the purposes, structure, and operative provisions of
175 this section, including the encouragement of long-term,
176 productive investment within Missouri opportunity zones and
177 the prevention of tax deferral without meaningful economic

SB 1668 55
178 activity. Rules promulgated under this subsection shall not
179 expand or restrict eligibility, alter the nature of
180 qualifying investments, or modify the deferral, inclusion,
181 or exclusion mechanics established by this section. Any
182 rule or portion of a rule, as that term is defined in
183 section 536.010, that is created under the authority
184 delegated in this section shall become effective only if it
185 complies with and is subject to all of the provisions of
186 chapter 536 and, if applicable, section 536.028. This
187 section and chapter 536 are nonseverable and if any of the
188 powers vested with the general assembly pursuant to chapter
189 536 to review, to delay the effective date, or to disapprove
190 and annul a rule are subsequently held unconstitutional,
191 then the grant of rulemaking authority and any rule proposed
192 or adopted after August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
✓

